    "excerpt": "When every major studio passed, a mid-size distributor took a chance that changed the industry.",
    "body": "Twelve months ago, the director behind this year's most talked-about film couldn't get a meeting. Three studios had passed on the script. Two agencies declined to represent the project. The conventional wisdom was clear: too long, too dark, too risky.\n\nThen a mid-size distributor with a reputation for backing outliers stepped in with a $200 million commitment — the largest in the company's history. The decision was met with scepticism from analysts and outright ridicule on industry message boards.\n\n'The script was unlike anything I'd read,' the distributor's head of acquisitions told us. 'It was ambitious in a way that made people nervous. But nervousness and quality are not the same thing.'\n\nThe production itself was gruelling. A 120-day shoot across four countries. A lead actor who demanded script rewrites every weekend. A cinematographer who quit twice and was hired back three times. The budget ballooned by 40 per cent before post-production even began.\n\nBut what emerged from that chaos was something extraordinary. Early test screenings produced the kind of silence that executives dream about — audiences too absorbed to check their phones. Festival premieres earned standing ovations lasting more than ten minutes.\n\nThe film has since grossed over $800 million worldwide, making it the most profitable original property in the distributor's history. More importantly, it has shifted the conversation about what mid-budget studios can accomplish.\n\n'The lesson isn't that risk always pays off,' the director said during our interview. 'The lesson is that the things that make people nervous are often the things that make stories worth telling.'",
