    "excerpt": "Cast and crew reveal what really happened on the day that changed cinema.",
    "body": "The scene lasted four minutes and twenty-three seconds on screen. It took eleven days to shoot. It required the construction of the largest practical set in the studio's history, the coordination of over 800 extras, and the invention of a camera technique that had never been used before.\n\nAnd it almost didn't happen.\n\n'We were two days from cutting it entirely,' the director admitted during our extensive interview about the sequence that critics have called the most important scene in cinema this decade. 'The studio was nervous. The insurance company was nervous. I was nervous, frankly. But I knew that if we didn't do it practically, the audience would feel the difference.'\n\nThe scene in question — a recreation of a historical event involving hundreds of participants — required a level of logistical planning more commonly associated with military operations than film production. A dedicated team of forty coordinators spent three months mapping every movement, every camera angle, every potential point of failure.\n\nThe lead actor, who is at the centre of the sequence, recalled the experience with a mixture of pride and lingering disbelief. 'There's a moment in the middle of the scene where I genuinely forgot I was acting. The scale of it — the noise, the movement, the heat — it was overwhelming. And I think that's what the audience feels too.'\n\nThe scene has since been viewed over 500 million times across social media platforms.",
