    "body": "It happened at a private dining room in the Beverly Hills Hotel on a Tuesday evening in March. Three CEOs — heading the entertainment divisions of companies worth a combined $2 trillion — sat down to dinner with no assistants, no legal teams, and no agenda distributed in advance.\n\nThe meeting lasted four hours. By the time it ended, the fundamental economics of the streaming industry had been redrawn.\n\n'I can't tell you who initiated it,' said a source with direct knowledge of the conversation. 'But I can tell you that everyone in that room understood that the current model was unsustainable. The spending had to rationalise. The question was whether it would happen through coordination or through chaos.'\n\nWhat emerged was a framework — not a formal agreement, which would raise antitrust concerns, but a shared understanding — about content spending, licensing windows, and the future of theatrical releases. Within six weeks, all three companies announced changes to their programming strategies that aligned closely with the themes discussed that evening.\n\nThe immediate impact was felt across the industry. Production deals that had been in development for months were suddenly cancelled. Green-lit projects were shelved. Entire development teams were restructured.\n\n'It was like someone turned off a tap,' one veteran producer told us. 'One week we had more work than we could handle. The next, the phone stopped ringing.'",
