    "title": "How a TikTok Creator Became Hollywood's Most Sought-After Producer",
    "excerpt": "From 15-second videos to $100 million deals — the most unlikely career in entertainment.",
    "body": "Three years ago, Marcus Chen was editing videos on a second-hand laptop in his parents' basement in suburban Ohio. His TikTok account, which featured short comedy sketches about everyday life, had just crossed one million followers.\n\nToday, Chen sits in a corner office on the Warner Bros. lot, overseeing a production slate worth over $100 million. His company, which he founded with two college friends, has produced three of the ten most-watched streaming series of the past year.\n\n'The transition wasn't as dramatic as people think,' Chen told us during a rare break between meetings. 'Storytelling is storytelling. The platform changes, but the fundamentals don't. You need characters people care about, stakes that feel real, and a point of view that's genuinely yours.'\n\nThe path from social media to studio production was paved with strategic decisions that, in hindsight, reveal a sophistication well beyond Chen's twenty-six years. Rather than chasing viral moments, he invested in developing longer-form content. Rather than accepting the first studio offers, he built a team. Rather than leveraging his personal brand, he created intellectual property that existed independently of him.\n\nThe Hollywood establishment was initially sceptical. 'I had executives tell me to my face that social media people don't understand narrative,' Chen recalled. 'I smiled, thanked them for their time, and made a note to prove them wrong.'",
