    "excerpt": "A filmmaker's decade-long investigation into corporate corruption faces unprecedented censorship.",
    "body": "Director Sarah Okonkwo spent ten years making her latest documentary. She was followed by private investigators, threatened with lawsuits in three countries, and had her footage seized twice by authorities. The film, which exposes a multinational corporation's role in environmental destruction across two continents, has been banned in two countries and is the subject of active legal proceedings in a third.\n\n'Every time we got close to releasing, something would happen,' Okonkwo told us from an undisclosed location in Europe. 'Legal threats. Pressure on distributors. Informants suddenly going silent. It was like hitting a wall that kept moving.'\n\nThe documentary draws on over 400 hours of footage, interviews with more than sixty whistleblowers, and thousands of internal corporate documents obtained through sources within the company. Its central allegation — that the corporation knowingly contaminated water supplies affecting over two million people — has been independently verified by two academic institutions.\n\nDespite the suppression efforts, the film has found its audience. A guerrilla distribution strategy — including encrypted file sharing and pop-up screenings in affected communities — has ensured that the documentary has been seen by an estimated fifty million people worldwide.\n\n'The irony is that the censorship became the story,' Okonkwo said. 'People who would never have watched a two-hour documentary about corporate malfeasance watched it because someone told them they couldn't.'",
