    "title": "Breaking Down the Record-Breaking World Tour That Shattered Every Record",
    "excerpt": "How one artist turned a stadium tour into a cultural phenomenon — by the numbers.",
    "body": "When the tour was announced eighteen months ago, industry observers were cautiously optimistic. Stadium tours are expensive, logistically complex, and inherently risky. When the tour concluded last month, it had grossed $2.2 billion — making it the highest-earning concert tour in history.\n\nThe numbers are staggering. 124 shows across 42 countries. Over 8 million tickets sold. An average attendance of 65,000 per show. A merchandise operation that generated more revenue than some entire record labels.\n\nBut the financial success, remarkable as it is, tells only part of the story. The tour also represented a fundamental shift in how live entertainment is produced and consumed.\n\nThe stage design alone took three years to develop, involving engineers from NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory and architects who had previously designed Olympic opening ceremonies. The result was a 360-degree performance space that could be assembled and disassembled in under twelve hours.\n\n'The goal was to create something that couldn't be replicated on a screen,' the tour's creative director told us. 'We wanted every person in that stadium to feel like they were the only person in the stadium.'\n\nTicket pricing was deliberately accessible, with the cheapest seats starting at $49 — significantly below market rate for an artist of this stature. 'Music should be for everyone,' the artist said during our interview. 'The economics work because we make them work, not because we price out the fans.'",
