    "excerpt": "A data-driven breakdown of viewership, subscriber growth, and breakout hits.",
    "body": "The summer of 2026 has been the most competitive period in streaming history. Six major platforms released original programming at a rate that made weekly viewing schedules nearly impossible to track. The result was a fragmented landscape where no single show dominated the cultural conversation the way previous summer hits had.\n\nThe numbers tell a clear story. Platform A led in total viewership hours, driven by the return of its flagship drama series and a surprise hit comedy that generated over 40 million streams in its first weekend. Platform B led in subscriber growth, adding 12 million new accounts — largely attributed to a Korean drama that became an unexpected global phenomenon.\n\nPlatform C had the most critically acclaimed programming, with three of the top five highest-rated series of the summer, but struggled to convert critical success into subscriber numbers. Platform D won the documentary race with a true-crime series that dominated social media conversation for six consecutive weeks.\n\nThe most interesting trend, however, was not about any single platform. It was about the audience. Viewership data suggests that the average subscriber now maintains 3.4 active streaming subscriptions — up from 2.8 last year. Churn rates have stabilised, suggesting that the market is maturing.\n\n'The streaming wars are over,' one analyst told us. 'What we're seeing now is the streaming equilibrium — a stable market where multiple platforms coexist because they serve different audience needs.'",
