    "cat": "INTERVIEW",
    "title": "Candid Conversations: Rising Stars on Fame, Pressure, and Authenticity",
    "excerpt": "Three breakout actors open up about the reality of sudden stardom.",
    "body": "The three actors sitting across from us in a Soho hotel suite have something in common beyond their youth and talent: each experienced a dramatic rise to fame within the past eighteen months. One starred in the year's highest-grossing film. Another anchored a streaming series that generated over 500 million viewing hours. The third delivered a performance so devastating that it earned an Oscar nomination for a debut role.\n\nWhat's striking about the conversation is how candid they are about the difficulties of sudden fame. 'Nobody prepares you for the loss of anonymity,' says the first. 'You go from being a person to being a product. People project their expectations onto you. Your face becomes public property.'\n\nThe second nods in agreement. 'The hardest part isn't the work — the work is what I trained for. The hardest part is the stuff around the work. The social media scrutiny. The paparazzi. The feeling that every mistake is permanent and public.'\n\nThe third, the youngest of the three at twenty-two, describes a different kind of pressure: the pressure to be grateful. 'Everyone tells you how lucky you are. And you are lucky. But gratitude doesn't make the anxiety go away. It just makes you feel guilty for being anxious.'\n\nDespite these challenges, all three express a deep commitment to their craft and a determination to build careers that last. 'I don't want to be famous,' says the first. 'I want to be good. The fame is just a side effect of being good at something people notice.'",
