    "excerpt": "Critics weigh in on the films most likely to dominate the upcoming awards circuit.",
    "body": "With six months until the ceremony, the awards race is already taking shape. A handful of films have emerged as frontrunners, while several late-year releases could still disrupt the field.\n\nThe current favourite is a historical drama that premiered at Venice to rapturous reviews and has since dominated the festival circuit. The film, which tells the story of a little-known chapter of American history, combines the kind of sweeping narrative that voters love with the intimate character work that critics reward.\n\nClose behind is a contemporary drama that tackles social media and mental health with a directness that has divided audiences but united critics. The film's lead performance — a career-best turn from an actor previously known for lighter fare — has been described as 'transformative' by multiple awards watchers.\n\nThe dark horse in the race is an independent film that was made for under $5 million and has since grossed over $200 million worldwide. Its director, a first-time filmmaker in her late twenties, would be the youngest person ever nominated in the Best Director category.\n\nThe biggest question mark hangs over a prestige biopic that has been plagued by behind-the-scenes drama and mixed early reactions. The film's subject — a towering figure in American cultural history — gives it built-in gravitas, but the execution has reportedly divided test audiences.\n\nAwards season is always unpredictable, but this year's race feels particularly open. 'There's no obvious frontrunner,' one veteran awards consultant told us. 'Which makes it the most interesting race in years.'",
