    "title": "Box Office Report: Summer Blockbusters by the Numbers",
    "excerpt": "Which franchises delivered, which disappointed, and what it means for Hollywood.",
    "body": "The summer box office season has concluded with a total domestic gross of $5.8 billion — a 12 per cent increase over last year and the highest summer total since 2019. But the headline number masks a more complicated reality.\n\nThe top three films — all sequels or franchise instalments — accounted for nearly 40 per cent of the total. The fourth-highest-grossing film of the summer was an original property, marking a rare victory for non-franchise filmmaking.\n\nThe biggest surprise was the underperformance of a heavily marketed sequel that was expected to dominate the season. The film opened strong but dropped 68 per cent in its second weekend — the steepest decline for a film of its budget size in recent memory.\n\nThe biggest overperformer was a modestly budgeted horror film that opened in sixth place and climbed to third over the following month, driven by exceptional word-of-mouth and a social media campaign that went viral organically.\n\nThe international numbers tell an even more interesting story. A film that underperformed domestically grossed over $600 million internationally, driven by exceptional performance in China and South Korea. The global marketplace continues to reshape Hollywood's economic calculations.\n\n'The lesson of this summer is that audiences are more discerning than we give them credit for,' one studio executive told us. 'They'll show up for quality, regardless of whether it has a number after the title.'",
